goals.question: What is the distribution of group sizes?
goals.rationale: This helps to understand the number of people in each group and if there are any outliers.

goals.question: What is the most common group size?
goals.rationale: This helps to identify the most common group size and if there are any groups with significantly more or fewer members.

goals.question: Which person is a member of the most groups?
goals.rationale: This helps to identify the most active member and if there are any individuals who are not part of any group.

goals.question: What is the distribution of the number of groups each person belongs to?
goals.rationale: This helps to understand the distribution of group membership and if there are any individuals who are part of an unusually high or low number of groups.

goals.question: Are there any groups with the same members?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of group and person
goals.rationale: This helps to identify any duplicate groups and if there are any individuals who are part of multiple identical groups.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['group'], bins=range(1,5), edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['group'].mean(), color='red', label='Mean: {:.2f}'.format(data['group'].mean()))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of group sizes?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    group_sizes = data.groupby('group').count()['person']
    plt.bar(group_sizes.index, group_sizes.values)
    plt.axvline(x=group_sizes.idxmax(), color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Most common group size: {group_sizes.max():.2f}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the most common group size?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    person_groups = data.groupby('person')['group'].count().sort_values(ascending=False)
    person_groups.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title('Which person is a member of the most groups?', wrap=True)
    plt.axhline(y=person_groups.iloc[0], color='r', linestyle='-')
    plt.legend([f"Max: {person_groups.iloc[0]:.2f}"])
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    person_group_count = data.groupby('person')['group'].count()
    plt.hist(person_group_count, bins=range(1, max(person_group_count)+2), align='left', rwidth=0.8)
    plt.axvline(person_group_count.mean(), color='red', label=f'Mean: {person_group_count.mean():.2f}')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Groups')
    plt.ylabel('Number of People')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of the number of groups each person belongs to?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    groups = data.groupby('person')['group'].apply(list).reset_index(name='groups')
    groups['group_count'] = groups['groups'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
    groups = groups[groups['group_count'] > 1]
    groups = groups.explode('groups')
    groups = groups.groupby('groups')['person'].apply(list).reset_index(name='people')
    groups['people_count'] = groups['people'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
    groups = groups[groups['people_count'] > 1]
    groups = groups.explode('people')
    groups['people'] = pd.Categorical(groups['people'], categories=groups['people'].unique(), ordered=True)
    groups = groups.sort_values(by=['groups', 'people'])
    groups['group'] = pd.Categorical(groups['groups'], categories=groups['groups'].unique(), ordered=True)
    groups = groups.sort_values(by=['group', 'people'])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    ax.scatter(groups['group'], groups['people'], s=100, alpha=0.7)
    ax.set_xlabel('Group')
    ax.set_ylabel('Person')
    ax.set_title('Are there any groups with the same members?')
    ax.grid(True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
